This paper deals with training deep neural networks for video classification using webly-supervised data. The primary focus is on learning appearance and temporal features sequentially, which falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also discusses domain adaptation and attention mechanisms, which are common topics in machine learning (cs.LG) and multimedia (cs.MM) research. Additionally, the use of search engine results for webly-supervised data suggests a potential overlap with information retrieval (cs.IR) research. Finally, the paper involves natural language processing techniques for text-based search queries, which could also fall under the computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category.
